# Pull request style

Write PRs the way CTNicholas does: short, plain, and information-dense. Default
to less. A reviewer should understand the change in a few seconds.

## Titles

- Keep it short and descriptive. Capitalize the first word; otherwise use
  sentence case (not Title Case). Proper feature names keep their casing (e.g.
  `AI`, `CHANGELOG`).
- No trailing period.
- Write "get started" in lowercase (e.g. "AI Comments get started guide").
- Optionally prefix with a scope and a colon when it helps, especially for
  examples: `Example:` for one, `Examples:` for several.
  - e.g. `Example: Add AI comments to AI dashboard`
  - e.g. `Examples: Add AI comments to various`
- Good examples: `New AI get started guides`,
  `Update comment streaming in dashboard example`,
  `Remove outdated private beta mentions`.

## Descriptions

- Be concise. For trivial changes, a single sentence (or even an empty body) is
  fine. Don't pad.
- Do NOT use PR-template-style headings such as `## Description`,
  `## Implementation notes`, or `## How to test it`. Just write the content
  directly.
- When there's more than one change, lead with a one-sentence summary, then a
  bullet list. Format names, paths, and identifiers in backticks, followed by a
  short description after a colon:
  - `` - `nextjs-ai-presence`: Show AI presence in avatar stacks ``
- Reference related PRs and issues as bare URLs on their own lines.
- For visual or UI changes, include evidence: screenshots via `<img ...>` and
  videos via `<video>` / attachment URLs.
- Tuck long supplementary content (prompts, large code samples, examples) inside
  `<details><summary>…</summary> … </details>`.
- Track follow-up work with bold `**TODO**` / `**TODO AFTER**` sections using
  checkbox lists (`- [ ]` / `- [x]`).
- Plain tone. No emoji. No marketing language. No "this PR…" preamble when a
  direct statement works.

## Anti-patterns (avoid)

- Long, sectioned write-ups with multiple `##` headings for a small change.
- Restating the diff line by line.
- Boilerplate "How to test" / "Risks" sections unless genuinely useful.
- Title Case titles or trailing periods in the title.
